## Why This Is Asked

Tests practical CSS layout decisions, motion handling, and accessibility for a common directory UI.

## Key Concepts

- CSS Grid responsive columns with media queries
- aspect-ratio and equal card sizing
- entrance animation with stagger using nth-child
- hover/focus accessible action panel
- prefers-reduced-motion and keyboard focus
- avoiding CLS via reserved space and transforms

## Code Example

```html
<!-- minimal card snippet -->
<div class="team-grid">
  <div class="team-card" aria-label="Member name: Role">
    <img class="team-card__avatar" src="..." alt=""/>
    <div class="team-card__name">Name</div>
    <div class="team-card__badge">Badge</div>
    <div class="team-card__actions">
      <button>Message</button>
      <button>View</button>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
```

```css
 .team-grid {
   display: grid;
   grid-template-columns: repeat(5, 1fr);
   gap: 16px;
 }
 @media (max-width: 1200px) { .team-grid { grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr); } }
 @media (max-width: 768px) { .team-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }

 .team-card {
   position: relative;
   aspect-ratio: 1 / 1;
   border-radius: 8px;
   overflow: hidden;
   background: #f3f4f6;
   animation: fadeUp 0.3s var(--i) both;
 }
 .team-card__avatar { width: 100%; height: 100%; object-fit: cover; }
 @keyframes fadeUp { from { opacity: 0; transform: translateY(12px); } to { opacity: 1; transform: translateY(0); } }
 @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) { .team-card { animation: none; } }

 .team-card__actions {
   position: absolute; bottom: 0; left: 0; right: 0;
   transform: translateY(100%);
   display: flex; justify-content: space-around; gap: 8px;
   padding: 8px; background: rgba(0,0,0,.5); color: #fff;
   transition: transform .25s;
 }
 .team-card:hover .team-card__actions,
 .team-card:focus-within .team-card__actions { transform: translateY(0); }
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you adapt this for dynamic updates that add/remove cards without causing jitter?
- How would you ensure keyboard-only users can access the actions panel without the card stealing focus?

## Why This Is Asked

Assess practical CSS grid skills, responsive breakpoints, and accessible motion. The candidate must show how to implement a non-shifting overlay reveal using absolute positioning and transform, with clean fallbacks for users who disable motion.

## Key Concepts

- CSS Grid with explicit breakpoints and repeat()
- aspect-ratio for poster sizing
- overlay reveal via transform to avoid CLS
- focus-visible and prefers-reduced-motion
- nested flexbox for caption alignment

## Code Example

```css
.grid{ display:grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(5, 1fr); gap:16px; }
@media (max-width:1200px){ .grid{ grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);} }
@media (max-width:900px){ .grid{ grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);} }
.card{ position:relative; height:260px; overflow:hidden; }
.poster{ width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover; aspect-ratio:16/9; display:block; }
.overlay{ position:absolute; left:0; right:0; bottom:0; padding:12px; background: rgba(0,0,0,.6); color:#fff; transform: translateY(100%); opacity:0; transition: transform .25s, opacity .25s; }
.card:hover .overlay, .card:focus-within .overlay{ transform: translateY(0); opacity:1; }
@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce){ .overlay{ transition:none; } }
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you adapt this pattern to support keyboard-only navigation without visual jitter?
- What accessibility tests would you run to ensure the overlay remains readable on all devices?

## Why This Is Asked
This tests advanced CSS mastery including masonry-like layouts with CSS Grid, CSS-only interactivity without JavaScript, accessibility implementation, and responsive design principles.

## Key Concepts
- Masonry layouts using CSS Grid's `grid-auto-rows` and `grid-row: span N`
- CSS-only filtering through checkbox inputs and CSS sibling selectors
- Responsive column adaptation across breakpoints
- Accessibility considerations: focus management, keyboard navigation, ARIA labels
- Motion preferences with `prefers-reduced-motion` media queries

