## Why This Is Asked

Tests mastery of modern CSS layout: two-pane grids, CSS-only UI state (no JS), and production-friendly animation with accessibility in mind. It also checks how candidates balance visual polish with stability at scale.

## Key Concepts

- CSS Grid two-pane layouts with responsive breakpoints
- CSS-only toggle for mobile collapsible rail
- grid-auto-columns and minmax for fluid card grids
- subtle entrance animations with stagger and motion preferences
- accessibility: focus-visible outlines and reduced-motion handling

## Code Example

```css
.grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 240px 1fr; gap: 16px; }
@media (max-width: 800px) {
  .grid { grid-template-columns: 48px 1fr; }
}
.card { animation: fadeUp .4s var(--delay) both; }
@keyframes fadeUp { from { transform: translateY(8px); opacity:0 } to { transform: translateY(0); opacity:1 } }
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you adapt this with container queries for nested components with variable content heights?
- How would you verify accessibility across assistive technologies and ensure robust reduced-motion behavior?

## Why This Is Asked
Demonstrates architectural thinking for a reusable timeline with CSS Grid and no JS for layout, while enforcing accessibility and motion constraints.

## Key Concepts
- Grid with alternating placement for left/right alignment
- Central timeline line via pseudo-element
- Animation timing with per-item delays
- Responsive switch to single column; prefers-reduced-motion

## Code Example
```javascript
/* CSS sketch for timeline grid and item styles */
.timeline{ display:grid; grid-template-columns:1fr auto 1fr; gap: 1rem;}
.timeline > .item{ display:flex; align-items:center; padding:1rem; }
.timeline > .item:nth-child(odd){ grid-column:1 / 2; justify-content:flex-end; }
.timeline > .item:nth-child(even){ grid-column:3 / 4; justify-content:flex-start; }
.timeline:before{ content:''; grid-column:2; width:2px; background:#bbb; align-self:stretch; }
@media (max-width: 800px){ .timeline{ grid-template-columns:1fr; } .timeline:before{ display:none; } }
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would accessibility be affected if the timeline contained long content?
- How would you adapt for dynamic data loading with CSS only?

## Why This Is Asked

