For optimistic updates, you separate the optimistic UI state from the actual server state. Here's a useReducer implementation:

```javascript
const initialState = {
  data: null,
  status: 'idle', // 'idle' | 'pending' | 'success' | 'error'
  previousData: null,
  error: null
};

function reducer(state, action) {
  switch (action.type) {
    case 'OPTIMISTIC_UPDATE':
      return {
        ...state,
        previousData: state.data,
        data: action.payload,
        status: 'pending'
      };
    case 'SUCCESS':
      return {
        ...state,
        status: 'success',
        previousData: null
      };
    case 'ERROR':
      return {
        ...state,
        status: 'error',
        data: state.previousData, // rollback
        previousData: null,
        error: action.error
      };
    default:
      return state;
  }
}

// Usage in component:
const [state, dispatch] = useReducer(reducer, initialState);

const handleUpdate = async (newData) => {
  dispatch({ type: 'OPTIMISTIC_UPDATE', payload: newData });
  try {
    await api.update(newData);
    dispatch({ type: 'SUCCESS' });
  } catch (error) {
    dispatch({ type: 'ERROR', error });
  }
};
```

The useState approach uses useEffect for the server call:

```javascript
const [data, setData] = useState(null);
const [isPending, setIsPending] = useState(false);
const [error, setError] = useState(null);

const handleUpdate = async (newData) => {
  const previousData = data;
  setData(newData); // optimistic update
  setIsPending(true);
  try {
    await api.update(newData);
  } catch (error) {
    setData(previousData); // rollback
    setError(error);
  } finally {
    setIsPending(false);
  }
};
```

For race conditions with multiple rapid updates, use AbortController to cancel in-flight requests:

```javascript
const abortRef = useRef(null);

const handleUpdate = async (newData) => {
  // Cancel any in-flight request
  abortRef.current?.abort();

  const controller = new AbortController();
  abortRef.current = controller;

  setData(newData); // optimistic
  try {
    await api.update(newData, { signal: controller.signal });
  } catch (error) {
    if (error.name !== 'AbortError') {
      setData(previousData);
    }
  }
};
```

Alternatively, use version/sequence tracking to ignore stale responses:

```javascript
const versionRef = useRef(0);

const handleUpdate = async (newData) => {
  const currentVersion = ++versionRef.current;
  setData(newData);
  try {
    await api.update(newData);
    if (currentVersion !== versionRef.current) return; // stale response
    // process success
  } catch (error) {
    if (currentVersion !== versionRef.current) return;
    setData(previousData); // rollback
  }
};
```

Key strategies: 1) Store previous state before optimistic update, 2) Use AbortController to cancel stale requests, 3) Track request version to ignore outdated responses, 4) Consider a queue for sequential processing of dependent updates.

questions.answer:
- Architecture: Call Stack, Macrotask Queue (setTimeout, UI events, I/O), Microtask Queue (Promise callbacks, async continuations), plus the Rendering step between turns.
- Execution order: 1) Run the current task to completion. 2) Drain the Microtask Queue (FIFO) until empty. 3) If needed, render/paint. 4) Dequeue and run the next Macrotask. 5) After each Macrotask, drain any newly scheduled Microtasks again. Microtasks scheduled during a macrotask are executed before the next macrotask.
- Microtasks vs Macrotasks: microtasks have higher priority and can accumulate; they run at the end of the current task, not after a render, and before the next macrotask. Macrotasks start a new turn.
- Async/await impact: await pauses execution and schedules the rest of the function as a microtask, so subsequent code runs only after microtask flushing but before the next macrotask. Repeated awaits create long microtask sequences; if you need real UI responsiveness, break long chains with a real macrotask (e.g., setTimeout) or rAF.
- Example:
```js
console.log('start');
Promise.resolve().then(() => console.log('micro'));
setTimeout(() => console.log('macro'), 0);
async function f(){ console.log('f start'); await Promise.resolve(); console.log('f after'); }
f();
console.log('end');
```
- Diagram:
```mermaid
flowchart TD
A[Call Stack] --> B{Microtask Queue empty?}
B -- Yes --> C[Macrotask Queue]
C --> A
B -- No --> D[Run microtask]
D --> B
```

