questions.explanation:
Closures enable functional patterns: private state, currying, and memoization. Trade-offs: closures keep references alive, increasing memory footprint; avoid capturing huge objects. Edge cases: loops with var can close over the wrong index; use let. In UIs, closures can lead to stale state if components re-render without updating bindings; debouncing/memoization illustrate how closures bind behavior to a specific creation context. Debounce example:
```
const debounce = (fn, wait) => {
  let t;
  return (...args) => {
    clearTimeout(t);
    t = setTimeout(() => fn(...args), wait);
  };
};
```

