## Why This Is Asked

This question evaluates understanding of closures, in-memory caching, and request deduplication—concepts that form the foundation of efficient API client design. It represents a practical pattern that reduces redundant network traffic while exposing a clean, simple API.

## Key Concepts

- **Closures** to encapsulate private cache state inaccessible from outside
- **In-flight deduplication** to coalesce concurrent requests for the same endpoint, avoiding duplicate network calls
- **TTL-based cache invalidation** using timestamp tracking to determine freshness
- **Async/await** for clean, readable asynchronous API exposure
- **URL construction** and normalization for consistent cache keys

## Code Example

```javascript
function createApiClient(baseUrl, ttlMs) {
  const cache = new Map();
  const inFlight = new Map();

  return {
    async get(path) {
      const url = new URL(path, baseUrl).toString();
      const now = Date.now();
      const cached = cache.get(url);

      if (cached && now - cached.timestamp < ttlMs) {
        return cached.data;
      }

      if (inFlight.has(url)) {
        return inFlight.get(url);
      }

      const promise = fetch(url).then(res => res.json());
      inFlight.set(url, promise);

      const data = await promise;
      cache.set(url, { data, timestamp: now });
      inFlight.delete(url);

      return data;
    },

    clear() {
      cache.clear();
      inFlight.clear();
    }
  };
}

// Usage
const client = createApiClient('https://api.example.com', 60000);
const users = await client.get('/users?limit=10');
```

